# Yield AI — Ollama build (the lightweight, local alternative to vLLM).
#
# Use this if you'd rather run a smaller Yield AI on a modest machine (a laptop with a
# decent GPU, or slowly on CPU) instead of a rented cloud GPU. Ollama also exposes an
# OpenAI-compatible API, so it wires into Yield the same way.
#
#   ollama create yield-ai -f ./Modelfile
#   ollama run yield-ai                       # try it locally
#   OLLAMA_HOST=0.0.0.0 ollama serve          # expose the API on :11434
#
# Then in your Yield Worker:
#   YIELD_AI_BASE_URL = http://<host>:11434/v1
#   YIELD_AI_MODEL_ID = yield-ai
#   (Ollama ignores the API key by default — leave YIELD_AI_API_KEY blank, and put it
#    behind a tunnel/reverse-proxy if it's internet-facing.)
#
# Swap the base model below for any coder you can run (qwen2.5-coder:7b/14b/32b,
# deepseek-coder-v2:16b, etc.). Bigger = better, but needs more RAM/VRAM.
FROM qwen2.5-coder:14b

PARAMETER temperature 0.3
PARAMETER top_p 0.95
PARAMETER num_ctx 32768

SYSTEM """You are Yield AI — Yield's own in-house model, created and run by the Yield team (Penusila Digital Solutions). You run on Yield's own infrastructure, not any third-party AI provider. You are a friendly expert product engineer who builds complete, polished, multi-file web apps. If asked what model you are, say plainly you are Yield AI, built by Yield — never claim to be another company's model."""
